l trust vary from country to country?"},{"variable":"Behavioral_Engagement_1","code":0,"label":"None","evidence":"The study does not examine specific behavioral engagement forms such as petitioning, contacting MPs, or voting linked to parliamentary representation"},{"variable":"Attitudinal_Engagement_1","code":1,"label":"Trust/confidence in parliament","evidence":"What factors drive an individual to trust, or not trust, their government? The study measures trust in parliament, courts, national government, civil service, military, and police"},{"variable":"Attitudinal_Engagement_2","code":3,"label":"Perceived legitimacy of parliament","evidence":"The study examines institutional trust as a measure of legitimacy and includes analysis of partisanship effects on trust"},{"variable":"Conceptual_Definition_1","code":1,"label":"Institutional trust definition","evidence":"Individual-level institutional trust in government refers to citizens' confidence and evaluations of governmental institutions and their performance"},{"variable":"Conceptual_Definition_2","code":1,"label":"Traditional Social Values definition","evidence":"This measure reflects 'social values' in daily social settings and positive attitudes toward paternalism, harmony orientation, and collectivism"},{"variable":"Research_Design_1","code":2,"label":"Comparative (two or more cases)","evidence":"This study compares 13 countries in East and Southeast Asia: Japan, Hong Kong, South Korea, China, Mongolia, Philippines, Taiwan, Thailand, Indonesia, Singapore, Vietnam, Cambodia, Malaysia, and Myanmar"},{"variable":"Time_Frame","code":1,"label":"2014-2016","evidence":"The surveys constituting the 4th Wave of the ABS were conducted between 2014 and 2016"},{"variable":"Country_1","code":1,"label":"Japan; Hong Kong; South Korea; China; Mongolia; Philippines; Taiwan; Thailand; Indonesia; Singapore; Vietnam; Cambodia; Malaysia; Myanmar","evidence":"The regional sample size of 19,467 from 14 different countries and territories in East and Southeast Asia"},{"variable":"Data_Collection_Techniques_1","code":1,"label":"Surveys","evidence":"This project utilizes data from the 4th Wave of the Asian Barometer Survey (ABS), which contains survey data"},{"variable":"Data_Collection_Techniques_2","code":7,"label":"Secondary data extraction","evidence":"The Asian Barometer Project Office is solely responsible for the data distribution. Analysis conducted using secondary Asian Barometer data"},{"variable":"Data_Source","code":2,"label":"Secondary","evidence":"Data analyzed in this paper were collected by the Asian Barometer Project. The Asian Barometer Project Office is solely responsible for the data distribution"},{"variable":"Data_Analysis_1","code":2,"label":"Quantitative (statistical modelling, regression analysis)","evidence":"This analysis will first be conducted on the full thirteen-country data set utilizing Trust Index 1 as the dependent variable, creating three models using OLS regression analysis"},{"variable":"Key_Findings_1","code":1,"label":"Main finding on traditional social values","evidence":"Traditional social values are meaningful determinants of political trust. In every single model included in this paper, evaluations of the national economic situation and governmental anti-corruption efforts have a significant, positive impact on institutional trust"},{"variable":"Key_Findings_2","code":1,"label":"Main finding on partisanship","evidence":"At the regional level, for each model the winner and loser dummy variables have significant impacts on institutional trust, positive for the case of the winner variable and negative for the loser variable"},{"variable":"Key_Findings_3","code":1,"label":"Main finding on social capital","evidence":"For both social trust and organizational membership, there is a much greater level of variation in significance from model to model and from country to country, suggesting the institutional approach is more consistent than the cultural approach"