ch_Questions_2","code":1,"label":"What democratic decision-making processes do citizens want?","evidence":"Nevertheless, it remains unclear what democratic decision-making processes citizens want."},{"variable":"Behavioral_Engagement_1","code":0,"label":"None","evidence":"Study measures attitudes through survey experiment vignette; no direct behavioral engagement measured"},{"variable":"Attitudinal_Engagement_1","code":1,"label":"Trust/confidence in parliament","evidence":"Confidence in political decision-making: A single measure indicating whether respondents felt that their confidence in political decision-making increased"},{"variable":"Attitudinal_Engagement_2","code":3,"label":"Perceived legitimacy of parliament","evidence":"Legitimacy index: Sum index based on six items measuring attitudes to aspects of input, throughput and output process legitimacy"},{"variable":"Conceptual_Definition_1","code":1,"label":"Legitimacy definition","evidence":"Legitimacy may be defined broadly as the capacity of a political system to engender and maintain the belief that existing institutions are the most appropriate or proper ones for the society"},{"variable":"Conceptual_Definition_2","code":1,"label":"Empirical legitimacy","evidence":"When understood in empirical terms, legitimacy is expected to hinge on citizens' beliefs and perceptions of political systems, processes or decisions rather than on independent criteria for legitimate procedures."},{"variable":"Research_Design_1","code":3,"label":"Experimental or quasi-experimental","evidence":"We examine these hypotheses with the help of a population-based survey experiment linked to a citizen initiative on the issue of euthanasia"},{"variable":"Time_Frame","code":1,"label":"December 2017","evidence":"Our data come from a survey experiment conducted during December 2017 in Finland"},{"variable":"Country","code":1,"label":"Finland","evidence":"Our experiment was conducted in a survey distributed via Qualtrics and responses collected 7–15 December 2017 during the hearings in the committee"},{"variable":"Data_Collection_Techniques_1","code":1,"label":"Surveys","evidence":"Our data come from a survey experiment conducted during December 2017 in Finland"},{"variable":"Data_Collection_Techniques_2","code":6,"label":"Experimental surveys","evidence":"A population-based survey experiment is an experiment that is administered to a representative population sample"},{"variable":"Data_Source","code":1,"label":"Primary","evidence":"The survey comprised an online sample including 1243 respondents stratified to reflect the general population structure"},{"variable":"Data_Analysis_1","code":1,"label":"Quantitative (descriptive, bivariate, statistical aggregation)","evidence":"Table 1 shows descriptive statistics for all variables"},{"variable":"Data_Analysis_2","code":2,"label":"Quantitative (statistical modelling, regression analysis)","evidence":"The main method of analysis is three way ANOVA where we examine the impact of our three factors including their interactions for each outcome measure"},{"variable":"Key_Findings_1","code":1,"label":"Outcome favorability is primary determinant of legitimacy","evidence":"The clearest result was that people perceive decisions as more legitimate when they get their preferred outcome (H1) since the results show that the most important determinant of process legitimacy is that people get the outcome that they prefer."},{"variable":"Key_Findings_2","code":1,"label":"Experts and citizens boost legitimacy over politicians","evidence":"people favour decision-making processes that involve ordinary citizens and experts over elected representatives deciding on their own"},{"variable":"Key_Findings_3","code":1,"label":"Justifications amplify outcome effects rather than cushion disappointment","evidence":"justiﬁcations here serve to intensify the differences. These findings are in line with research suggesting that arguments and information contradicting prior opinions can 